Sample sizes are adequate for a meaningful comparison: 306 VIP orders and 1,283 New orders. While VIP has fewer orders, 306 is still large enough that the observed mean is unlikely to be a sampling artifact, especially given the magnitude of the difference (nearly an order of magnitude). The total revenue figures (13.2M from VIP vs 7.9M from New) further corroborate that VIP customers, despite being fewer in number, generate more absolute revenue, consistent with a higher-value-per-order segment.

One caveat: without the distribution (median, variance, outliers), we cannot rule out that a small number of very large VIP orders skew the mean. However, even with skew, a 7x gap is difficult to explain away, and the hypothesis is framed around averages specifically. The data clearly supports the hypothesis as stated.", "verdict": "supported", "evidence_summary": "VIP customers' average order value (43,288.75) is approximately 7x higher than New customers' (6,174.40) across 306 and 1,283 orders respectively, clearly supporting the hypothesis."}
